var tafsirData_36 = {
  1: {
    "Yâ-Sĩn": "These are two Arabic letters that begin this Surah. Such letters, known as 'Huroof Muqatta'at' (disjointed letters), appear at the start of several Surahs in the Quran. Their exact meaning is known only to Allah. Some scholars suggest they serve to capture the listener's attention, demonstrating that the Quran, though composed of familiar Arabic letters, is a miraculous Book that no human could produce. This opening sets a tone of mystery and reverence, preparing the heart to receive what follows."
  },
  2: {
    "By the Quran, rich in wisdom!": "Allah swears by the Quran itself, highlighting its immense value and authority. When Allah takes an oath by something, it signifies its great importance. The Quran is described as 'Hakeem' (wise), meaning it is full of perfect wisdom, containing guidance that addresses every aspect of human life. It distinguishes between right and wrong, provides solutions to all problems, and leads humanity to success in this life and the Hereafter. This oath emphasizes that everything stated after it is absolute truth."
  },
  3: {
    "You ˹O Prophet˺ are truly one of the messengers": "This is a direct confirmation from Allah to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) that he is genuinely among the chosen messengers sent by Allah. The disbelievers of Makkah denied his prophethood, claiming he was a poet, a magician, or a madman. Allah emphatically affirms here, using strong grammatical emphasis in Arabic ('inna' and 'la'), that Muhammad is without doubt a true messenger, continuing the noble chain of prophets like Ibrahim, Musa, and Isa (peace be upon them all). This was a source of comfort for the Prophet during times of rejection and persecution."
  },
  4: {
    "upon the Straight Path": "The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) is not only a messenger, but he is also firmly established upon the Straight Path—the clear, direct way to Allah that has no crookedness or deviation. This path is Islam, the religion of pure monotheism, moral excellence, and submission to Allah. The same path was taught by all previous prophets. This verse reassures the Prophet and his followers that they are on the correct path, regardless of how many people oppose or reject them. The truth is not determined by the number of its followers but by its source—Allah Himself."
  },
  5: {
    "˹This is˺ a revelation from the Almighty, Most Merciful": "The Quran is not the words of Muhammad, nor the invention of any human being. It is a direct revelation sent down from Allah, Who is 'Al-Aziz' (the Almighty, the One with absolute power who cannot be overcome) and 'Ar-Raheem' (the Most Merciful, the One who shows special mercy to the believers). The combination of these two names is significant: Allah has the power to punish, yet He chooses to send guidance and mercy through His Book and His Messenger. This shows that the Quran is both a warning backed by divine power and a mercy offering salvation to those who accept it."
  },
  6: {
    "so that you may warn a people": "The purpose of sending the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) with this revelation was to warn people about the consequences of disbelief and sin, and to call them to the worship of Allah alone. Warning is an essential part of every prophet's mission—to make people aware of the Day of Judgment, accountability, and the reality of Hell and Paradise.",
    "whose forefathers were not warned": "The Arabs of Makkah had not received a prophet for a very long time. The period between Prophet Isa (Jesus) and Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon them) is called 'Fatrah'—a gap of approximately 600 years without a messenger. During this time, the Arabs fell into deep ignorance, worshipping idols, burying daughters alive, and engaging in all kinds of immoral practices. They had no recent divine guidance to follow.",
    "and so are heedless": "Because their ancestors were not warned and no prophet came to them for generations, these people became completely heedless and unaware of their Creator, the purpose of life, and the Hereafter. They were absorbed in worldly pursuits, tribal pride, and idol worship, completely neglecting their spiritual condition. This heedlessness (ghaflah) is one of the most dangerous spiritual diseases—being alive yet unaware of one's ultimate destination."
  },
  7: {
    "The decree ˹of torment˺ has already been justified against most of them": "Allah, in His infinite knowledge, knows who will choose to believe and who will stubbornly reject the truth despite clear evidence. For those who have made a firm decision to reject faith—not out of confusion but out of arrogance and deliberate denial—Allah's decree of punishment has become justified. This is not arbitrary; it is a consequence of their own choices. Allah does not wrong anyone; rather, people wrong themselves by choosing disbelief.",
    "for they will never believe": "These individuals have reached a point where they have closed all doors to guidance. They have seen the signs, heard the message, witnessed the Prophet's character, yet they chose to reject. Their hearts have become so hardened that faith cannot penetrate them. This is a profound warning about the danger of continuously rejecting truth—eventually, the heart becomes sealed. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'When a believer commits a sin, a black spot appears on his heart. If he repents, it is polished. But if he persists, it increases until it covers the whole heart' (Ibn Majah). This is the 'Ran' (covering) mentioned in the Quran."
  },
  8: {
    "˹It is as if˺ We have put shackles around their necks up to their chins": "This is a powerful metaphor describing the spiritual condition of those who stubbornly reject faith. Imagine a person with heavy iron shackles around their neck, so tight that the collar reaches up to their chin. Such a person cannot lower their head or move freely.",
    "so their heads are forced up": "Because of these metaphorical shackles, their heads are forced upward in an unnatural, rigid position. They cannot bow down in humility to Allah, they cannot lower their gaze to reflect on the signs around them, and they cannot submit. This imagery illustrates how pride and arrogance prevent a person from accepting truth. Just as physical shackles restrict movement, spiritual arrogance restricts the heart from bowing to its Creator. These people are imprisoned by their own egos, unable to see beyond their pride."
  },
  9: {
    "and have placed a barrier before them and a barrier behind them": "In addition to the shackles, Allah describes placing barriers in front of and behind these stubborn disbelievers. A barrier in front means they cannot see what lies ahead—the truth, guidance, and the consequences of their actions in the Hereafter. A barrier behind means they cannot learn from the past—the stories of destroyed nations, the lessons of history, and the fate of those who rejected prophets before them. They are completely blocked from benefiting from any source of guidance.",
    "and covered them ˹all˺ up, so they fail to see ˹the truth˺": "On top of the barriers, Allah has placed a covering over them, completely obscuring their vision. This is not physical blindness but spiritual blindness—the inability to perceive truth even when it is right in front of them. They hear the Quran but do not understand. They see the Prophet's miracles but dismiss them. They witness the signs in creation but remain unmoved. This is the ultimate consequence of repeatedly rejecting guidance: Allah seals the heart, and the person becomes spiritually blind. This should serve as a stern warning to anyone who takes guidance lightly or delays accepting truth."
  },
  10: {
    "It is the same whether you warn them or not—they will never believe": "For those whose hearts have been sealed due to their persistent rejection, the warning makes no difference. Whether the Prophet (peace be upon him) warns them repeatedly or remains silent, the outcome is the same—they will not believe. This is not because the warning is ineffective, but because they have made an irreversible choice to reject. This verse comforts the Prophet, who felt deep grief over his people's disbelief. Allah is telling him: do not exhaust yourself over those who have chosen misguidance. You are responsible for delivering the message, not for forcing people to accept it. As Allah says elsewhere: 'You cannot guide whom you love, but Allah guides whom He wills' (Quran 28:56)."
  },
  11: {
    "You can only warn those who follow the Reminder": "Your warning will only benefit those who are willing to follow the Quran (the Reminder). These are people with open hearts, who listen to guidance and act upon it. They are not arrogant; they recognize truth when they hear it and submit to it. The 'Reminder' refers to the Quran, which reminds humanity of their Creator, their purpose, and their final destination.",
    "and are in awe of the Most Compassionate without seeing Him": "These people fear Allah even though they have never seen Him. This is the essence of true faith—believing in and fearing Allah in the unseen (bil-ghayb). They do not need to see Paradise or Hell to believe; their hearts are convinced through faith. This fear is not terror but a reverential awe mixed with love, which prevents them from disobeying Allah. Notice that Allah uses the name 'Ar-Rahman' (the Most Compassionate) here, indicating that even the fear of Allah is connected to awareness of His mercy—they fear disappointing a Lord who has been so merciful to them.",
    "So give them good news of forgiveness and an honourable reward": "For these believing souls, the Prophet is instructed to deliver good news (bushra). What is this good news? First, complete forgiveness of all their sins—Allah will wipe away their mistakes and shortcomings. Second, an honorable reward (ajr kareem)—a generous, noble recompense in Paradise that befits the generosity of Allah. This reward is 'kareem' (noble/generous), meaning it is beyond imagination and far greater than anything they could have earned through their deeds alone. This verse gives immense hope to believers: no matter how many sins you have committed, if you turn to Allah with faith and fear, forgiveness and a beautiful reward await you."
  },
  12: {
    "It is certainly We Who resurrect the dead": "Allah emphatically affirms His power to bring the dead back to life. The word 'We' (in the royal sense) and the emphasis in Arabic make this statement absolutely certain. Many disbelievers denied resurrection, finding it impossible that scattered bones could be reassembled. Allah declares that He, Who created life from nothing, can surely restore it. The One who originates has no difficulty in repeating. This is a fundamental belief in Islam—that all humans will be resurrected on the Day of Judgment to be held accountable for their deeds.",
    "and write what they send forth and what they leave behind": "Allah records two categories of deeds. First, 'what they send forth'—the actions a person does during their lifetime, both good and bad: prayers, charity, sins, kindness, cruelty, etc. Second, 'what they leave behind'—the effects and legacy of their actions that continue after death. This includes good legacies like beneficial knowledge they taught, charity whose benefits continue (like building a mosque or digging a well), righteous children who pray for them, or positive traditions they started. It also includes negative legacies like harmful innovations, bad examples they set, or evil they initiated that others continue after them. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'When a person dies, their deeds end except for three: ongoing charity, knowledge that benefits others, and a righteous child who prays for them' (Muslim).",
    "Everything is listed by Us in a perfect Record": "Absolutely everything—every deed, word, thought, and intention—is recorded in a clear, comprehensive record. This is the 'Lauh al-Mahfuz' (the Preserved Tablet), the master record that contains everything that was, is, and will be. Nothing escapes Allah's knowledge, no matter how small or hidden. This should make every person conscious of their actions, knowing that everything is being recorded and will be presented on the Day of Judgment. There will be no denying or hiding on that Day."
  },
  13: {
    "Give them an example ˹O Prophet˺ of the residents of a town": "Allah instructs the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) to present a parable to the Quraysh and all who hear this message. This is a teaching method used throughout the Quran—using stories and examples to convey lessons. The 'town' is traditionally understood to be Antioch (Antakya in modern Turkey), though Allah knows best. The important point is not the exact location but the lesson it contains.",
    "when the messengers came to them": "This town received messengers sent by Allah (or according to some scholars, messengers sent by Prophet Isa/Jesus). The fact that Allah sent messengers shows His mercy—He does not punish a people without first sending them guidance and warning. This is consistent with Allah's justice: 'We never punish until We have sent a messenger' (Quran 17:15)."
  },
  14: {
    "We sent them two messengers, but they rejected both": "Initially, Allah sent two messengers to this town. Despite the clear message these messengers brought, the people rejected both of them. Rejection of messengers is a recurring theme in human history—most communities rejected their prophets initially. This shows how difficult the path of truth can be and how human beings often resist change, especially when it challenges their established way of life.",
    "So We reinforced ˹the two˺ with a third": "When the people rejected two messengers, Allah did not immediately punish them. Instead, out of His mercy, He sent a third messenger to reinforce the message and give the people another chance. This shows Allah's patience and His desire for people to be guided. Three messengers to one town—this is an abundance of guidance and an elimination of any excuse.",
    "and they declared, \"We have indeed been sent to you ˹as messengers˺\"": "The three messengers clearly and unambiguously declared their mission. They did not speak in riddles or hide their purpose. They openly proclaimed that they were sent by Allah to guide the people. Clarity in conveying the message is essential—true messengers do not hide or manipulate; they speak the truth plainly."
  },
  15: {
    "The people replied, \"You are only humans like us": "This was the classic objection raised against prophets throughout history. The disbelievers could not accept that God would choose human beings to deliver His message. They expected angels or supernatural beings. Yet this objection is baseless—human messengers are chosen precisely because they can relate to other humans, serve as practical examples, and live among the people they guide. Allah addresses this objection elsewhere: 'Say: If there were angels walking peacefully on earth, We would have sent them an angel messenger' (Quran 17:95).",
    "and the Most Compassionate has not revealed anything": "The disbelievers went further, denying that Allah had revealed anything at all. This is complete denial of divine revelation—a rejection of the concept that God communicates with humanity through prophets. Notice how they used the name 'Ar-Rahman' (the Most Compassionate) mockingly, despite not believing in Him.",
    "You are simply lying!": "The final accusation: they called the messengers liars. This is the most serious charge against someone claiming to speak on Allah's behalf. By calling them liars, the people were essentially claiming the messengers were fabricating the entire message for personal gain or attention. This is exactly what the Quraysh said to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), so this story directly parallels his experience."
  },
  16: {
    "The messengers responded, \"Our Lord knows that we have truly been sent to you": "The messengers responded with calm dignity. They did not argue or become defensive. Instead, they invoked Allah as their witness. By saying 'Our Lord knows,' they were essentially taking an oath by Allah's knowledge—the most serious testimony possible. They were absolutely certain of their mission, and they put their trust in Allah, Who knows the truth of all matters. This is how believers should respond to accusations: with patience, dignity, and reliance on Allah."
  },
  17: {
    "And our duty is only to deliver ˹the message˺ clearly": "The messengers clarified the scope of their responsibility. They were not tasked with forcing people to believe or with guaranteeing results. Their only duty was to deliver the message clearly and completely (al-balagh al-mubeen). The decision to accept or reject was left to the people, and the consequences were theirs to bear. This is an important principle: prophets and those who call to Islam are responsible for conveying the message sincerely and clearly, not for the outcome. This also relieved the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) of the burden of feeling responsible for every person's disbelief."
  },
  18: {
    "The people replied, \"We definitely see you as a bad omen for us": "The disbelievers resorted to superstition, blaming the messengers for any misfortune they experienced. This practice of seeing certain people or things as bad omens was common among ignorant societies. Instead of reflecting on their own sins as the cause of their problems, they blamed innocent messengers. This is a tactic of denial—externalizing blame rather than accepting responsibility.",
    "If you do not desist": "They issued an ultimatum: stop preaching or face consequences. This is the response of tyrants throughout history—silencing truth through threats rather than engaging with the message.",
    "we will certainly stone you ˹to death˺": "They threatened the most brutal form of execution—stoning. This shows how threatened they felt by the truth and how far they were willing to go to silence it.",
    "and you will be touched with a painful punishment from us": "Beyond stoning, they threatened additional torture and punishment. These empty threats revealed their desperation and their complete rejection of rational discourse. When people cannot defeat truth with arguments, they resort to violence."
  },
  19: {
    "The messengers said, \"Your bad omen lies within yourselves": "The messengers rejected the superstitious accusation and redirected it back to the people. Your misfortune is not because of us; it is because of your own disbelief and sins. Every person carries the consequences of their own choices. The real 'bad omen' was their rejection of guidance, which would lead to their destruction.",
    "Are you saying this because you are reminded ˹of the truth˺?": "The messengers pointed out the absurdity of the people's reaction. Is this how you respond to someone who reminds you of Allah and calls you to salvation? Is remembrance of truth a crime? Is good advice met with death threats? This rhetorical question exposes the irrationality of the disbelievers.",
    "In fact, you are a transgressing people": "The messengers concluded by diagnosing the real problem: the people were 'musrifoon'—transgressors who exceeded all limits. They had gone beyond bounds in their disbelief, their sins, and now their threats against innocent messengers. Transgression (israaf) means exceeding proper limits, and these people had abandoned all moral and spiritual boundaries."
  },
  20: {
    "Then from the farthest end of the city a man came, rushing": "At this critical moment, a man entered the scene. He came from the farthest part of the city, meaning he was not someone of central importance or influence in the town's power structure. Yet when he heard about the messengers and their message, he did not hesitate. He came 'rushing' (yas'a)—running with urgency. This shows his sincerity and eagerness to support the truth and prevent his people from making a fatal mistake. According to tradition, this man's name was Habib al-Najjar (Habib the Carpenter), a simple, righteous man who recognized truth when he saw it.",
    "He advised, \"O my people! Follow the messengers": "He addressed them lovingly as 'my people' (ya qawmi), showing that his advice came from genuine concern, not hostility. His message was simple and direct: follow the messengers. He did not engage in lengthy debates or philosophical arguments. The truth was clear, and the right response was equally clear—follow those whom Allah has sent."
  },
  21: {
    "Follow those who ask no reward of you": "The man gave his people a practical criterion to evaluate the messengers' sincerity. These messengers are not asking you for any payment, wealth, or worldly benefit in exchange for their guidance. They have no material motive. This is a hallmark of true prophets and sincere callers to truth—they seek no personal gain. If someone calls you to guidance while seeking money, power, or fame, their motives are questionable. But these messengers want nothing from you except your own salvation.",
    "and are ˹rightly˺ guided": "Furthermore, these messengers are themselves guided. They practice what they preach. Their lives reflect the truth they call to. When someone is genuinely guided by Allah, it shows in their character, their consistency, and their sincerity. The man urged his people to follow such trustworthy guides rather than persisting in their own misguidance."
  },
  22: {
    "And why should I not worship the One Who has originated me": "The man then turned to himself, presenting his own reasoning. He asked a rhetorical question: what possible reason could I have NOT to worship the One who created me? This is the most fundamental logic—the Creator deserves worship. The word 'fatara' means to originate, to create from nothing. Allah brought him into existence when he was nothing. How could he then turn away from his Creator and worship something else?",
    "and to Whom you will be returned": "He reminded them of the ultimate reality—all of them would return to Allah. Death is certain, and after death comes accountability. By mentioning their return to Allah, he was warning them that their choice to reject the messengers would have eternal consequences. Notice his wisdom: when speaking of creation, he said 'me' (personal), but when speaking of return, he said 'you' (addressing them directly). He was trying to awaken them to their own inevitable fate."
  },
  23: {
    "How could I take besides Him other gods": "The man posed another rhetorical question, dismantling the logic of idol worship. Why would I take gods besides Allah—gods that I have made with my own hands or that others have invented?",
    "whose intercession would not be of any benefit to me": "These false gods cannot intercede for anyone. Intercession (shafa'ah) means to plead on someone's behalf. The idolaters believed their gods would intercede for them with the supreme God. But the man pointed out that these idols have no power to intercede whatsoever. They cannot speak, they cannot help, and they have no influence with Allah.",
    "nor could they save me if the Most Compassionate intended to harm me": "If Allah, in His wisdom, decreed some difficulty or harm for the man, could these idols rescue him? Absolutely not. They cannot prevent what Allah has decreed, nor can they provide what Allah has withheld. So what is the point of worshipping them? The man used beautiful logic to expose the absurdity of idolatry."
  },
  24: {
    "Indeed, I would then be clearly astray": "The man concluded his argument with a powerful statement. If I were to worship these powerless idols instead of the Almighty Creator, I would be in 'dalal mubeen'—clear, obvious, undeniable misguidance. There would be no excuse, no justification. Anyone who worships something that cannot hear, see, benefit, or harm is clearly lost. This statement was both a personal declaration and an indirect warning to his people: if I would be astray for doing this, what about you who are actually doing it?"
  },
  25: {
    "I do believe in your Lord, so listen to me": "The man made his declaration of faith publicly and boldly. He said 'your Lord'—meaning the Lord that you should also believe in, the true Lord of everyone, the Lord proclaimed by the messengers. He had accepted faith, and he wanted his people to know. 'So listen to me' was his final plea—a desperate appeal from a sincere heart that wanted nothing but good for his community. Despite knowing the potential consequences of publicly declaring faith before a hostile crowd, he did not remain silent. His faith gave him courage to speak truth regardless of the danger."
  },
  26: {
    "˹But they killed him, then˺ he was told ˹by the angels˺, \"Enter Paradise!\"": "The people did not listen to the believing man. Instead, they killed him for his faith—a martyr for the truth. The Quran does not detail how he was killed, but various reports suggest he was stoned, trampled, or killed violently by the mob. However, immediately upon his death, he was given the greatest news possible: 'Enter Paradise!' There was no waiting, no delay. His soul was welcomed directly into the gardens of eternal bliss. This is the ultimate success—what greater honor could there be than immediate entry into Paradise?",
    "He said, \"If only my people knew": "Remarkably, even in this moment of ultimate personal triumph, the man's first thought was about his people. He did not curse them for killing him or rejoice at their coming punishment. Instead, he wished they could see what he was seeing—the truth of faith, the reality of Paradise, the honor Allah had bestowed upon him. This shows the incredible nobility and compassion of a true believer. His heart was so pure that even after being murdered by his own people, he wished for their guidance. This is the character Islam builds—love for others' salvation even when they have wronged you."
  },
  27: {
    "of how my Lord has forgiven me": "If only his people knew of the complete forgiveness Allah had granted him. All his sins were wiped away. This is what matters in the end—not worldly status, wealth, or power, but whether Allah has forgiven us. The man, who was a simple carpenter from the outskirts of town, received complete divine forgiveness.",
    "and made me one of the honourable": "Not only was he forgiven, but Allah made him among the 'mukrameen'—the honored ones. He was elevated to a status of nobility in Paradise. The same man whom his people despised, threatened, and killed was honored by the Lord of all creation. This is the great reversal of the Hereafter: those whom the world rejected may be the most honored with Allah, and those whom the world celebrated may be the most disgraced. This story of the believing man from the town serves as a powerful reminder that speaking truth, even at the cost of one's life, is the path to eternal honor. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said about this man: 'He was sincere to his people in life and in death' (from scholars' commentary)."
  },
  28: {
    "We did not send any soldiers from the heavens against his people after his death": "After the believing man was martyred, Allah did not need to send down armies of angels or any heavenly forces to punish his killers. When people imagine divine punishment, they might envision grand armies or elaborate supernatural events. But Allah's power is far beyond such need. He does not require an army to execute His will. This also shows that the town's people were so insignificant in their rebellion that they did not even warrant a grand display of divine power.",
    "nor did We need to": "Allah emphasizes that He had no need for such measures. His power is absolute and His command is sufficient. When He decides to punish a people, He does not need elaborate means. This statement humbles the arrogant disbelievers—they thought they were powerful when they killed the believing man, but in reality, they were utterly insignificant before Allah's might."
  },
  29: {
    "All it took was one ˹mighty˺ blast": "The punishment was swift and simple—just one blast, one mighty sound (sayhah). This could have been a thunderous cry from Angel Jibreel or a catastrophic natural disaster. The point is that it required minimal effort from Allah's perspective. One single blast was sufficient to destroy an entire town of arrogant disbelievers who had rejected three messengers and killed a righteous believer.",
    "and they were extinguished at once": "The word 'khaamidoon' means extinguished like a flame that has been put out, or like embers that have died down to nothing. One moment they were alive, threatening, and arrogant; the next moment they were lifeless, silent, and finished. Their lives ended as quickly as a candle being blown out. This imagery emphasizes how fragile human life is and how quickly Allah can end the existence of those who rebel against Him. All their power, wealth, and arrogance meant nothing when Allah's command came."
  },
  30: {
    "Oh pity, such beings!": "This is an expression of deep sorrow and regret—'Ya hasratan' means 'what a pity' or 'alas for them.' Allah, or the angels, or even the heavens themselves express grief over these servants of Allah who destroyed themselves through their own stubbornness. They had every opportunity for guidance but chose mockery and rejection instead. How tragic that human beings, given the gift of intellect and the blessing of messengers, would squander their chance at salvation.",
    "No messenger ever came to them without being mocked": "This is a sorrowful pattern throughout human history. Whenever Allah sent a messenger to guide people—whether Nuh, Ibrahim, Musa, Isa, or Muhammad (peace be upon them all)—the response of most people was mockery and ridicule. They laughed at the message, insulted the messenger, and made jokes about the warnings. This reflects the disease of human arrogance: instead of humbly considering the message, people mock what they don't understand or what threatens their lifestyle. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) faced the same treatment from the Quraysh, who called him a poet, madman, and liar."
  },
  31: {
    "Have the deniers not considered how many peoples We destroyed before them": "Allah poses a powerful rhetorical question to the disbelievers of Makkah and all who reject truth. Have they not reflected on history? Have they not seen the ruins of destroyed civilizations? The people of Nuh were drowned, the people of 'Ad were destroyed by wind, the people of Thamud were struck by earthquake, the people of Lut were overturned. These are not myths—their remains and ruins were visible to the Arabs who traveled for trade. History is full of lessons for those who reflect.",
    "who never came back to life again": "Once these nations were destroyed, they never returned. They did not get a second chance in this world. Their opportunity for repentance ended with their death. This is a warning: do not assume you have unlimited time to accept the truth. The nations before you thought the same, and they were destroyed while still in denial. They never came back to rebuild, to repent, or to try again. Their worldly chapter was closed permanently."
  },
  32: {
    "Yet they will all be brought before Us": "Although these destroyed nations did not return to this world, they will all be resurrected and gathered before Allah on the Day of Judgment. No one escapes divine accountability. Every individual from every nation—those who believed and those who rejected—will stand before their Lord. This verse connects the punishment in this world with the greater accountability in the Hereafter. The destruction was only the beginning; the real reckoning is yet to come. This should make every person pause and consider their own standing with Allah."
  },
  33: {
    "There is a sign for them in the dead earth": "Allah now directs attention to the natural world as evidence of His power, particularly His ability to resurrect. Look at the earth when it is dead—dry, barren, lifeless, with no vegetation or movement. This is a 'sign' (ayah)—a proof and evidence that points to a greater truth.",
    "We give it life, producing grain from it for them to eat": "When Allah sends rain upon this dead earth, it springs to life. Seeds that lay dormant suddenly sprout, and the earth becomes green and productive. From this once-barren land comes grain—wheat, barley, rice—that sustains human life. If Allah can bring dead earth back to life, can He not bring dead human beings back to life on the Day of Resurrection? This is one of the most powerful proofs of resurrection that the Quran presents. The One who transforms barren soil into fields of grain can surely transform scattered bones into living bodies again."
  },
  34: {
    "And We have placed in it gardens of palm trees and grapevines": "Beyond basic grain, Allah has blessed the earth with lush gardens containing palm trees (which produce dates, a staple food in Arabia) and grapevines (which produce grapes, raisins, and other benefits). These are not just functional—they are beautiful, providing shade, fruit, and aesthetic pleasure. Allah did not merely provide sustenance; He provided abundance and variety.",
    "and caused springs to gush forth in it": "In addition to rain from above, Allah causes fresh water to spring from within the earth. Springs and underground wells provide water even in dry seasons and arid regions. Water is life, and Allah has embedded it within the very earth that humans walk upon. All of this—the gardens, the fruits, the springs—emerges from earth that was once dead and barren. This transformation should fill the heart with wonder and gratitude."
  },
  35: {
    "so that they may eat from its fruit": "The purpose of all this provision is for human benefit. People eat the fruits of these gardens—dates, grapes, and countless other produce. Their bodies are nourished, their hunger satisfied, and their lives sustained.",
    "which they had no hand in making": "Here is a profound reflection: although humans may plant seeds and tend gardens, they did not create the seeds, the soil, the water, or the process of growth. They cannot make a single seed sprout by their own power. The entire system of agriculture is a gift from Allah that humans merely participate in. The farmer plants, but Allah grows. Human hands did not design photosynthesis, did not program seeds to know how to become plants, did not create the nutrients in soil. All of this is from Allah.",
    "Will they not then give thanks?": "Given all these blessings that humans did not create and could never create, should they not be grateful? Should they not recognize their Creator and thank Him? This rhetorical question exposes the ingratitude of those who enjoy Allah's countless blessings yet refuse to acknowledge Him. Gratitude (shukr) is one of the most fundamental responses a human being should have toward Allah. Denying Him while eating His provision is the height of ingratitude."
  },
  36: {
    "Glory be to the One Who created all ˹things in˺ pairs": "Allah is glorified (Subhan Allah)—He is far above any imperfection or partner. One of His amazing signs is the creation of pairs throughout existence. The concept of pairs (azwaj) is fundamental to creation.",
    "—˹be it˺ what the earth produces": "Plants have male and female parts or require pollination between different plants. Fruits come from paired reproductive processes. This was not fully understood scientifically until recently, yet the Quran mentioned it over 1400 years ago.",
    "their genders": "Human beings and animals exist as male and female pairs. This pairing is essential for reproduction and the continuation of species. The complementary nature of genders is a sign of Allah's wisdom.",
    "or what they do not know": "Beyond what humans can observe, there are pairs they do not yet know about. Modern science has discovered that even subatomic particles have pairs (matter and antimatter, positive and negative charges). There may be countless other pairs in creation that humans have yet to discover. This phrase shows the Quran's timeless nature—it acknowledges knowledge beyond what was available at the time of revelation. All of this pairing points to a single Creator who designed everything with purpose and balance."
  },
  37: {
    "There is also a sign for them in the night": "The night itself is another sign pointing to Allah's power and control over the universe. Every evening, humans witness this sign without reflecting on it deeply.",
    "We strip from it daylight": "Allah uses the word 'naslakhu' which means to strip off or peel away, like removing skin from an animal. This vivid imagery describes how Allah peels away the daylight, gradually removing the brightness until only darkness remains. The transition from day to night is so smooth and consistent that people take it for granted, yet it is a remarkable cosmic event that occurs with perfect precision.",
    "then —behold!—they are in darkness": "Suddenly, people find themselves in darkness. The word 'fa idha' (then behold) suggests a dramatic moment of realization. Without the light that Allah provides through the sun, humans would be plunged into complete darkness. They have no control over this process—they cannot delay the night or summon the day. This daily occurrence should remind them of their dependence on Allah and His complete control over their environment. The One who controls light and darkness controls everything."
  },
  38: {
    "The sun travels for its fixed term": "The sun is not stationary—it travels (tajri means to run or flow). Modern astronomy confirms that the sun moves through space, orbiting the center of our galaxy at tremendous speed while also having its own rotational motion. It has a 'mustaqarr'—a fixed term or destination appointed by Allah. This could refer to its eventual end or its daily cycle of appearing to set. Nothing in creation is random or eternal except Allah Himself.",
    "That is the design of the Almighty, All-Knowing": "This precise movement of the sun is not accidental. It is 'taqdeer'—the precise measurement and design of Allah. He is 'Al-Aziz' (the Almighty, having complete power) and 'Al-Aleem' (the All-Knowing, having complete knowledge). The combination of power and knowledge means Allah designed the solar system with perfect precision. Scientists have discovered that even slight variations in the sun's position or energy output would make life on Earth impossible. This perfect calibration is the work of the All-Knowing Creator."
  },
  39: {
    "As for the moon, We have ordained ˹precise˺ phases for it": "The moon has been given 'manazil'—stations or phases that it passes through in its monthly cycle. From new moon to crescent to half moon to full moon and back again, the moon follows a precise schedule. These phases are so regular that humans have used them to create calendars for thousands of years. The Islamic calendar is lunar, and the sighting of the moon determines the beginning of each month, including Ramadan and the Hajj season. This orderly system was designed by Allah for human benefit.",
    "until it ends up like an old, curved palm stalk": "At the end of its monthly cycle, the crescent moon becomes extremely thin and curved, resembling an old, dried palm branch that has curved with age. This beautiful simile draws on imagery familiar to the Arabs—the 'urjoon' is the stalk that holds dates on a palm tree. When old and dry, it becomes thin and curved, just like the waning crescent moon. This poetic description demonstrates the Quran's literary beauty while conveying scientific accuracy."
  },
  40: {
    "It is not for the sun to catch up with the moon": "The sun and moon each have their own orbits and cannot interfere with each other. The sun cannot 'catch' the moon, meaning their movements are independent yet perfectly coordinated. Neither collides with the other, and neither disrupts the other's path. This cosmic order has been maintained for billions of years without fail.",
    "nor does the night outrun the day": "Similarly, night and day follow each other in perfect sequence. Night does not suddenly overtake day prematurely, nor does day last forever. The transition is gradual, predictable, and reliable. This consistency allows life on Earth to flourish—plants depend on this cycle for photosynthesis, animals depend on it for their biological rhythms, and humans depend on it for work and rest.",
    "Each is travelling in an orbit of their own": "Every celestial body—the sun, the moon, the stars, the planets—is swimming (yasbahoona) in its own orbit (falak). The word 'swimming' beautifully describes how these massive objects move smoothly through space as if floating in water. Modern astronomy confirms that celestial bodies travel in precise orbits. This verse, revealed 1400 years ago, accurately describes orbital mechanics that humans only fully understood in recent centuries. This is the perfect design of the Creator."
  },
  41: {
    "Another sign for them is that We carried their ancestors ˹with Noah˺ in the fully loaded Ark": "Allah presents another sign of His power and mercy: the story of the Ark of Nuh (Noah). When the great flood came and destroyed the disbelieving world, Allah saved the believers by carrying them in a fully loaded ship. The word 'dhurriyyatahum' (their offspring/ancestors) indicates that all humans alive today are descendants of those who were saved on the Ark. Everyone's existence is owed to that act of divine mercy. The Ark was 'mashoon'—fully loaded with people, animals, and provisions. This miraculous salvation is a sign that Allah has power over water and can save whomever He wills."
  },
  42: {
    "and created for them similar things to ride in": "Just as Allah enabled the Ark to carry people across the flood, He has created for subsequent generations similar vessels—ships and boats that carry people across seas and rivers. The knowledge to build ships, the properties of water that allow boats to float, the winds that fill sails—all of this is from Allah's design and provision. Humans may think they invented maritime travel, but it was Allah who created the natural laws that make it possible and inspired the knowledge to utilize them."
  },
  43: {
    "If We willed, We could drown them": "All maritime safety depends entirely on Allah's will. He could, if He wished, cause ships to sink and passengers to drown. The same seas that carry people safely can become their graves in an instant. Storms, waves, and disasters are all under Allah's command.",
    "then no one would respond to their cries": "If Allah decreed drowning, no coast guard, no rescue ship, no emergency service could save them. Their cries for help would go unanswered. In the vastness of the ocean, human beings are utterly helpless without Allah's protection.",
    "nor would they be rescued": "There would be no last-minute rescue, no miraculous survival. When Allah decrees something, no force in the universe can prevent it. This should instill both fear and gratitude—fear of Allah's power and gratitude for His constant protection that most people take for granted."
  },
  44: {
    "except by mercy from Us": "The only reason people survive sea voyages—or any danger in life—is because of Allah's mercy (rahmah). It is not their skill, their technology, or their luck. It is purely Allah's mercy that allows them to reach their destinations safely.",
    "allowing them enjoyment for a ˹little˺ while": "This safety and survival is temporary—'ila heen' means for a limited time. Allah extends people's lives so they may enjoy the blessings of this world for a while longer. But this extension has a purpose: it is an opportunity to recognize Allah, worship Him, and prepare for the Hereafter. Eventually, everyone's time will end. The wise person uses this borrowed time for earning Allah's pleasure, not for heedless enjoyment."
  },
  45: {
    "˹Still they turn away˺ when it is said to them, \"Beware of what is ahead of you ˹in the Hereafter˺\"": "Despite all the signs and warnings, when the disbelievers are advised to fear what lies ahead—the Day of Judgment, the accounting of deeds, Heaven and Hell—they turn away in arrogance. They refuse to contemplate their future with Allah.",
    "and what is behind you ˹of destroyed nations˺": "They are also warned to learn from the past—the destroyed nations who rejected prophets before them. The ruins of 'Ad, Thamud, the people of Lut—all serve as historical lessons. But the disbelievers refuse to look back and learn.",
    "so you may be shown mercy": "The purpose of these warnings is not to scare people pointlessly but to help them attain Allah's mercy. If they would only heed the warnings, they could avoid punishment and earn divine mercy. Yet they reject this advice, sealing their own fate through stubborn denial."
  },
  46: {
    "Whenever a sign comes to them from their Lord, they turn away from it": "The problem is not lack of evidence—signs come to them constantly. The universe is full of signs, the Quran is full of signs, the Prophet's life is a sign. But whenever any sign reaches them, their response is consistent: they turn away (mu'rideen). They deliberately avert their attention, refusing to engage with the evidence. This is willful ignorance, not genuine confusion. They have chosen to reject, so no amount of signs will convince them."
  },
  47: {
    "And when it is said to them, \"Donate from what Allah has provided for you,\"": "When the disbelievers are encouraged to spend in charity from the wealth that Allah has given them, to help the poor and needy, they refuse. They are asked to share what was never truly theirs to begin with—everything comes from Allah.",
    "the disbelievers say to the believers, \"Why should we feed those whom Allah could have fed if He wanted to?": "The disbelievers respond with a twisted argument. They say: if Allah wanted these poor people to be fed, He would have fed them Himself. Why should we do it? This response is deeply flawed. First, it shows they acknowledge Allah could feed the poor but then they reject His command to be the means of that feeding. Allah often accomplishes His will through human hands—He provides rain, but humans must farm. He provides resources, but humans must distribute them. Second, this argument is just an excuse for selfishness disguised as theology. They don't actually care about divine will; they simply don't want to share their wealth.",
    "You are clearly astray!\"": "The disbelievers accuse the believers of being misguided for encouraging charity. This is an inversion of reality—the truly misguided are those who refuse to share Allah's blessings with the needy. The disbelievers project their own misguidance onto the believers."
  },
  48: {
    "And they ask ˹the believers˺, \"When will this threat come to pass, if what you say is true?\"": "The disbelievers mockingly ask about the timing of the Day of Judgment. Their question is not sincere seeking of knowledge but arrogant dismissal. They say: if you're truthful about this coming punishment, tell us when exactly it will happen. This demand for precise timing reveals their disbelief—they think that if it were real, it would happen immediately or on a predictable schedule. They fail to understand that Allah's timing is based on His wisdom, not human impatience."
  },
  49: {
    "They must be awaiting a single Blast": "What they are unknowingly waiting for is just one Blast (sayhah)—the same type of blast that destroyed the town in the earlier verses. This will be the Blast of the Trumpet that signals the end of the world.",
    "which will seize them while they are ˹entrenched˺ in ˹worldly˺ disputes": "The Blast will come suddenly, without warning. It will catch people while they are engaged in their daily arguments and disputes—business dealings, petty quarrels, marketplace haggling. Life will be going on normally, and then suddenly it will end. This is a powerful reminder: the Hour could come at any moment, so one should not postpone repentance or righteous deeds. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'The Hour will not come until two men spread out a cloth between them and they will not be able to complete their transaction or fold it up' (Bukhari)."
  },
  50: {
    "Then they will not be able to make a ˹last˺ will": "When the Blast comes, there will be no time to put affairs in order. People will not be able to dictate their wills, divide their inheritance, or give final instructions. Everything will happen too suddenly for any preparation.",
    "nor can they return to their own people": "Those who are away from home will not have the chance to return to their families to say goodbye or seek forgiveness. The separation will be immediate and final. This is why Islam emphasizes maintaining good relationships constantly—one never knows when death or the Hour will come. Every meeting could be the last, so every parting should be with love and forgiveness."
  },
  51: {
    "The Trumpet will be blown ˹a second time˺": "After the first Blast that ends all life, there will be a second blowing of the Trumpet (Sur). This second blast will resurrect all of creation. Angel Israfil is assigned to blow this Trumpet by Allah's command.",
    "then—behold!—they will rush from the graves to their Lord": "Immediately upon hearing the second Blast, all human beings who ever lived will emerge from their graves. They will 'yansiloon'—move quickly, streaming out like water or rushing forward. From every grave on earth, from every corner of land and sea where human remains have been scattered, people will rise and move toward their Lord for judgment. This image of countless billions rushing from their graves is overwhelming to contemplate."
  },
  52: {
    "They will cry, \"Woe to us!": "The disbelievers will cry out in distress—'Ya waylana' is an expression of extreme grief and despair. The reality they denied has now become inescapable.",
    "Who has raised us up from our place of rest?": "They will be confused and horrified. They refer to their graves as their 'resting place' (marqad), as if death was sleep and resurrection is a rude awakening. For the believers, death is rest before the joy of meeting Allah. But for disbelievers, this 'rest' is now over, and accountability begins.",
    "This must be what the Most Compassionate warned us of; the messengers told the truth!\"": "In that moment of resurrection, the truth becomes crystal clear. They acknowledge that this is exactly what Ar-Rahman (the Most Compassionate) promised and what the messengers warned about. They finally admit: the messengers told the truth. But this admission comes too late. On that Day, belief will not benefit those who did not believe before. The time for faith was during life, not after resurrection when the truth is undeniable."
  },
  53: {
    "It will only take one Blast": "Just as their worldly lives ended with one Blast, their resurrection requires only one Blast. Allah's power is absolute—He does not need repeated attempts or complex processes. One command, one sound, and the entire system operates.",
    "then at once they will all be brought before Us": "Instantly, all of humanity—every person who ever lived from Adam to the last person—will be gathered before Allah. No one will be missing, no one will escape, no one will be able to hide. The gathering (hashr) will be complete and immediate. The accounting is about to begin."
  },
  54: {
    "On that Day no soul will be wronged in the least": "Allah's justice on the Day of Judgment will be perfect and absolute. No person will be treated unfairly, not even by the smallest amount. Good deeds will not be diminished, and no one will be punished for sins they did not commit. Allah is 'Al-Adl'—the Just—and His judgment reflects perfect justice.",
    "nor will you be rewarded except for what you used to do": "Every person will receive exactly what they earned through their actions. Good for good, bad for bad, with Allah's mercy enhancing the reward for believers and His justice ensuring fair punishment for disbelievers. This is the ultimate accountability that gives meaning to all human choices. Every deed matters, every intention counts, and nothing is forgotten or overlooked."
  },
  55: {
    "Indeed, on that Day the residents of Paradise will be busy enjoying themselves": "While the disbelievers face terror and accountability, the people of Paradise will be in an entirely different state. They will be 'fi shughulin fakihoon'—occupied with enjoyment, busy with pleasure. They will have no worries, no fears, no regrets. Their occupation will be pure bliss—enjoying the rewards Allah has prepared for them. This contrast highlights the vastly different outcomes awaiting believers and disbelievers. The same Day that brings horror to some brings eternal happiness to others."
  },
  56: {
    "They and their spouses will be in ˹cool˺ shade": "The believers will be with their spouses—their righteous partners from this world or the companions of Paradise. Together, they will be in pleasant, cool shade. For people of Arabia, shade represented relief from the scorching sun—a symbol of comfort and luxury. In Paradise, there is no harsh sun, only perfect, pleasant shade.",
    "reclining on ˹canopied˺ couches": "They will recline on 'ara'ik'—luxurious couches or thrones with canopies. Reclining suggests complete relaxation and ease, the posture of someone with no worries and nothing to fear. These are not ordinary seats but thrones of honor befitting the guests of Allah. Every description of Paradise emphasizes comfort, honor, and complete satisfaction."
  },
  57: {
    "There they will have fruits": "Fruits of every kind will be available to them—fruits familiar and fruits beyond imagination. Unlike worldly fruit that is seasonal or spoils, the fruits of Paradise are eternal and perfect, always ripe, always delicious, always within reach.",
    "and whatever they desire": "Beyond fruits, they will have anything they wish for. The Arabic 'ma yadda'oon' means whatever they call for or desire. If they wish for something, it appears. There are no unmet desires in Paradise, no frustration, no wanting. Every wish is fulfilled, every desire satisfied. The Prophet (peace be upon him) described Paradise saying: 'In it is what no eye has seen, no ear has heard, and no human heart has conceived' (Bukhari and Muslim, from Quran 32:17)."
  },
  58: {
    "And \"Peace!\" will be ˹their˺ greeting from the Merciful Lord": "The greatest honor of all—Allah Himself will greet them with 'Salam' (Peace). The Lord of the Universe, the Creator of all that exists, the Most Merciful, will directly address the inhabitants of Paradise with a greeting of peace. This is beyond any worldly honor or achievement. To be greeted by one's Creator with peace is the ultimate success, the highest possible status. All the struggles of worldly life, all the tests and trials, all the patience and perseverance—it all culminates in this moment: Allah saying 'Salam' to His faithful servants. This single word encompasses complete safety, total satisfaction, eternal peace, and divine approval. May Allah make us among those who receive this greeting."
  },
  59: {
    "˹Then the disbelievers will be told,˺ \"Step away ˹from the believers˺ this Day, O wicked ones!": "After describing the bliss of the believers in Paradise, Allah now turns to the fate of the disbelievers. They will be commanded to separate themselves—'imtaazu' means to be distinguished, set apart, or isolated. On the Day of Judgment, there will be a clear separation between the people of Paradise and the people of Hell. No mixing, no confusion. The disbelievers are addressed as 'mujrimoon'—criminals, wicked ones, those who committed sins and rejected faith. This term emphasizes that they are being treated as criminals facing judgment for their crimes. The separation itself is a punishment—they are cut off from the righteous, from mercy, and from hope."
  },
  60: {
    "Did I not command you, O Children of Adam, not to follow Satan": "Allah will remind them of the covenant—the fundamental instruction given to all humanity since the beginning. Through revelation, through prophets, through innate conscience (fitrah), the message was clear: do not follow Satan. Do not obey him, do not worship him through following his suggestions, do not take his path. This command was given to all 'Children of Adam'—every human being without exception. No one can claim ignorance of this basic guidance.",
    "for he is truly your sworn enemy": "The reason for this command is explicit: Satan is humanity's clear, open, declared enemy ('aduwwun mubeen'). From the moment Adam was created, Satan vowed to mislead humanity. He does not hide his enmity—it is obvious and announced. Allah warned about this enemy repeatedly, yet people still followed him. How foolish to follow someone who openly declares they want to destroy you! The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Satan flows through the son of Adam like blood flows through his veins' (Bukhari and Muslim), highlighting how persistent this enemy is."
  },
  61: {
    "but to worship Me ˹alone˺?": "The command was twofold: reject Satan AND worship Allah alone. These are complementary—one cannot truly worship Allah while following Satan, and one cannot truly reject Satan without worshipping Allah. The command to worship Allah alone is the essence of all divine messages from Adam to Muhammad (peace be upon them all). Every prophet came with this same fundamental teaching.",
    "This is the Straight Path": "Worshipping Allah alone and rejecting Satan—this is the 'Sirat al-Mustaqeem,' the Straight Path. It is not complicated, not hidden, not ambiguous. The path was made clear, straight, and accessible. Those who rejected it have no excuse—they were shown the way and chose to deviate. The Straight Path is mentioned in Surah Al-Fatihah as the path of those whom Allah has blessed, and here it is defined simply as exclusive worship of Allah and rejection of Satan."
  },
  62: {
    "Yet he already misled great multitudes of you": "Despite all the warnings, Satan succeeded in misleading 'jibillan katheeran'—huge multitudes, vast numbers, great masses of people. Generation after generation fell into his traps. This is historical fact—most of humanity throughout history chose disbelief, idol worship, and disobedience. Satan's mission was tragically successful with most people.",
    "Did you not have any sense?": "Allah asks a piercing rhetorical question: did you not use your intellect (aql)? You saw nations before you destroyed for following Satan. You had revelation warning you. You had prophets guiding you. You had your own rational minds to distinguish right from wrong. Yet you still followed your sworn enemy into destruction. This is not just a crime—it is profound foolishness. The intellect Allah gave humans was meant to recognize truth and reject falsehood, but they abandoned reason and followed desires instead."
  },
  63: {
    "This is the Hell you were warned of": "Now they see it with their own eyes—Jahannam, Hell, the Fire. This is not a myth, not a scare tactic, not a metaphor. It is real, and now they are facing it. 'The Hell you were warned of'—every prophet warned about it, the Quran described it in detail, believers reminded them, yet they denied and mocked. Now denial is impossible. The very punishment they dismissed as fairy tales stands before them."
  },
  64: {
    "Burn in it Today for your disbelief": "The command is given: enter the Fire and burn in it—'islawha.' This is not arbitrary punishment but direct consequence: 'bima kuntum takfuroon'—because of what you used to deny/disbelieve. Their disbelief (kufr) is the reason for their punishment. They covered the truth, rejected the messengers, denied the signs, and dismissed the warnings. Now they face the result of those choices. The word 'today' (al-yawm) emphasizes the immediacy—the time for second chances has passed, the time for punishment has arrived."
  },
  65: {
    "On this Day We will seal their mouths": "On the Day of Judgment, the disbelievers will try to deny their sins, make excuses, or lie about their deeds. But Allah will seal their mouths so they cannot speak lies or denials. Their tongues, which they used to lie, mock, and deny in the world, will be silenced.",
    "their hands will speak to Us": "Instead of their mouths, their own hands will testify. The hands that committed sins—stealing, harming others, writing falsehood, gesturing obscenely—will speak and inform Allah of exactly what they did. These are not metaphorical hands but their actual limbs, given the power of speech by Allah.",
    "and their feet will testify to what they used to commit": "Similarly, their feet will bear witness—the feet that walked toward sin, that carried them to forbidden places, that moved in acts of transgression. Every limb will testify truthfully against its owner. This is the ultimate accountability—even one's own body becomes a witness. No denial is possible when your own hands and feet testify against you. This should make every believer conscious of what they do with every part of their body, knowing it will all be testified about."
  },
  66: {
    "Had We willed, We could have easily blinded their eyes": "Allah reminds the disbelievers of His absolute power over them. If He wished, He could obliterate their eyes—'tamas' means to wipe out, efface, or seal completely. They would become completely blind, unable to see anything at all. This is not an idle threat but a demonstration that their ability to see is entirely dependent on Allah's will.",
    "so they would struggle to find their way": "If blinded, they would frantically try to find their way, rushing toward the path (sirat) but unable to navigate. They would stumble, fall, and be completely lost.",
    "How then could they see?": "The rhetorical question emphasizes their helplessness: if Allah took their sight, how could they possibly see? They could not. This is a warning to use the blessing of sight properly—to see the signs of Allah and recognize truth—because the gift of vision can be taken away at any moment. It also shows that spiritual blindness, which they have chosen, is even worse than physical blindness."
  },
  67: {
    "And had We willed, We could have transfigured them on the spot": "Allah could also transform them completely—'masakhnaa' refers to transfiguration, changing their form into something else, perhaps animals or statues. This happened to some previous nations as punishment, like those who violated the Sabbath and were turned into apes (mentioned in Surah Al-Baqarah). If Allah willed, He could do the same to these disbelievers instantly, right where they stand.",
    "so they could neither progress forward nor turn back": "If transfigured, they would be frozen—unable to move forward or backward. They would be stuck in place, helpless, transformed. This emphasizes that human mobility, human form, human capability—all of it is a gift from Allah that can be revoked at any moment. The disbelievers walk arrogantly on Allah's earth, using Allah's blessings to disobey Him, yet He could freeze them in an instant."
  },
  68: {
    "And whoever We grant a long life, We reverse them in development": "Here Allah presents a sign that everyone witnesses: aging. When Allah grants someone a long life, He reverses their physical development—'nunakkishu fil-khalq.' A person starts helpless as a baby, grows strong in youth, then gradually weakens again in old age. Hair turns gray, bones become fragile, memory fades, strength diminishes. The elderly often become dependent on others, just like children. This reversal is a clear sign of Allah's control over human life and a reminder that this world is temporary.",
    "Will they not then understand?": "Do people not use their intellect to recognize these signs? Every person either dies young or lives to experience this reversal. Either way, human life demonstrates Allah's complete control. Those who live long enough to become old should recognize that the same power that weakened them can certainly resurrect them after death. Aging is proof that Allah can do whatever He wills with His creation."
  },
  69: {
    "We have not taught him poetry": "The disbelievers of Makkah, unable to deny the Quran's powerful effect, tried to dismiss it by calling Muhammad (peace be upon him) a poet. Allah firmly refutes this: We have not taught him poetry. The Prophet was not trained in poetry, did not compose poetry, and the Quran is fundamentally different from poetry in its structure, purpose, and effect. Arabic poetry followed specific meters and patterns; the Quran has its own unique style that does not conform to any poetic form.",
    "nor is it fitting for him": "Poetry is not befitting for the Prophet's mission. Poets were known for exaggeration, flights of fancy, and entertainment. The Prophet's role was far more serious—delivering divine truth for human salvation. The Quran is not entertainment or artistic expression; it is guidance from the Lord of the worlds. The Prophet himself rarely spoke in verse, and when poetry was recited, he would sometimes change the order of lines, showing it was not his natural mode of expression.",
    "This ˹Book˺ is only a Reminder": "The Quran is 'dhikr'—a Reminder. It reminds humanity of Allah, of their purpose, of the Hereafter, of their covenant with their Creator. It is not fiction, not fantasy, not artistic license. It is truth meant to awaken sleeping hearts.",
    "and a clear Quran": "It is 'Quran mubeen'—a clear, manifest recitation. The word Quran means 'that which is recited,' and 'mubeen' means clear, evident, and making things clear. The Quran clarifies truth from falsehood, guidance from misguidance, and the path to salvation from the path to destruction. Its clarity leaves no excuse for those who reject it."
  },
  70: {
    "to warn whoever is ˹truly˺ alive": "The purpose of the Quran is to warn those who are 'alive'—not physically alive, but spiritually alive. Those whose hearts are responsive, whose minds are open, whose souls seek truth—these are the truly living. A person can be breathing yet spiritually dead, with a heart sealed to guidance. The Quran benefits those who have spiritual life, who can receive and respond to its message. This echoes the earlier verse about warning only benefiting those who fear Allah without seeing Him.",
    "and fulfil the decree ˹of torment˺ against the disbelievers": "For those who reject despite the warning, the Quran serves to establish proof against them—'yahiqqa al-qawlu.' The decree of punishment becomes justified because they received clear warning and chose to reject. No one will be able to say they were not warned. The Quran serves as evidence on the Day of Judgment that every person was given the opportunity to believe."
  },
  71: {
    "Do they not see that We singlehandedly created for them, among other things, cattle": "Allah draws attention to another sign: domesticated animals, particularly cattle (an'aam—which includes camels, cows, sheep, and goats). These animals were created by Allah alone—'mimma 'amilat aydeena' is an expression meaning 'from what Our hands have made,' signifying direct divine creation. No one else was involved in creating these animals; they are purely from Allah's making.",
    "which are under their control?": "Despite being larger and stronger than humans, these animals are subdued and under human control. A small human child can lead a massive camel. A single shepherd can control an entire flock. This is not natural—these animals could easily overpower humans if they chose to. But Allah has made them submissive, allowing humans to benefit from them. This submission is a divine gift, not a result of human power."
  },
  72: {
    "And We have subjected these ˹animals˺ to them": "Allah explicitly states that He is the One who made these animals submissive—'dhallalnaha' means We made them tame, docile, subdued. Without this divine subjugation, humans could never use these animals. Wild animals are dangerous and uncontrollable; domesticated animals serve humanity because Allah designed them that way.",
    "so they may ride some": "Some of these animals serve as transportation—camels and horses carry people across vast distances, allowing travel, trade, and communication that would otherwise be impossible.",
    "and eat others": "Some animals provide meat for food—sheep, goats, and cattle are sources of protein that sustain human life. Allah created this entire system of human-animal relationship for human benefit."
  },
  73: {
    "And they derive from them other benefits": "Beyond riding and eating, humans derive many other benefits from animals—wool for clothing and shelter, skins for leather goods, bones for tools, manure for fertilizer and fuel. Animals also provide labor for farming and carrying goods. The list of benefits is extensive.",
    "and drinks": "Animals provide drinks—most notably milk, which comes from cows, goats, camels, and sheep. Milk is a complete food in itself, providing nutrition, hydration, and energy. From milk comes yogurt, cheese, butter, and other dairy products. All of this from animals that eat grass and produce pure, wholesome milk—a transformation that only Allah could design.",
    "Will they not then give thanks?": "The question returns: with all these blessings, will they not show gratitude? Animals serve humans in countless ways, asking nothing in return except basic care. This entire system is a gift from Allah. The appropriate response is gratitude (shukr)—acknowledging Allah as the source and worshipping Him in thanks. Yet many people use these blessings while denying the One who provided them."
  },
  74: {
    "Still they have taken other gods besides Allah": "Despite all of Allah's signs and blessings—the earth, the heavens, the animals, their own creation—the polytheists have taken other gods besides Allah. They worship idols, saints, celestial bodies, or other created beings. This is the ultimate ingratitude: using Allah's blessings while worshipping others.",
    "hoping to be helped ˹by them˺": "Their motivation is hope for help ('la'allahum yunsaroon')—they think these false gods will assist them, protect them, or intercede for them. They seek worldly benefits, victory over enemies, or salvation in the Hereafter from beings that have no power whatsoever. This hope is completely misplaced and will lead to bitter disappointment."
  },
  75: {
    "They cannot help the pagans": "The reality is stark: these false gods cannot help their worshippers at all. They have no power to protect, no ability to provide, no capacity to save. The worshippers call upon beings that cannot respond, cannot hear, cannot act.",
    "even though they serve the idols as dedicated guards": "The relationship is actually reversed from what the pagans imagine. Instead of the idols serving and protecting the worshippers, the worshippers end up serving the idols! They guard the statues, clean them, protect them from damage, and defend them from criticism. The idols become a burden on their worshippers, not a source of help. And on the Day of Judgment, these worshippers will be brought forth (muhdaroon) as soldiers of the idols—marched into Hell alongside the objects they worshipped. What a tragic irony: they sought help from beings that they themselves had to protect."
  },
  76: {
    "So do not let their words grieve you ˹O Prophet˺": "Allah consoles and strengthens His Prophet. The hurtful words of the disbelievers—their mockery, their accusations, their insults—should not cause the Prophet grief. Their rejection is not a reflection of his failure; it is their own loss. The Prophet cared deeply about his people's guidance, and their rejection pained him. But Allah tells him not to let this sadness overwhelm him.",
    "Indeed, We ˹fully˺ know what they conceal and what they reveal": "Nothing is hidden from Allah—not their public statements of rejection nor their private plots and hatred. Allah knows every secret thought, every whispered conspiracy, every hidden intention. This knowledge means they cannot escape accountability. Their public mockery and their private scheming are all recorded and will all be addressed. The Prophet should take comfort knowing that Allah is fully aware and will handle the matter with perfect justice."
  },
  77: {
    "Do people not see that We have created them from a sperm-drop": "Allah presents a powerful argument for resurrection by pointing to the origin of human life. Every human being came from a 'nutfah'—a tiny drop of fluid, a sperm-drop so small it cannot be seen by the naked eye. From this insignificant beginning, Allah created a complete human being with all their complexity.",
    "then—behold!—they openly challenge ˹Us˺?": "Despite this humble origin, the human being grows up and becomes 'khaseemun mubeen'—an open disputant, an argumentative challenger! The same creature who started as an invisible drop now has the audacity to argue with their Creator, denying His power to resurrect. This is the height of arrogance and ingratitude. The verse expresses amazement at human audacity: look at what you came from, and look at how you behave!"
  },
  78: {
    "And they argue with Us—forgetting they were created": "The disbelievers construct arguments against resurrection, completely forgetting the most relevant evidence: their own creation. They forget that they once did not exist, then Allah brought them into being. If Allah could create them from nothing the first time, why would the second creation be difficult?",
    "saying, \"Who will give life to decayed bones?\"": "This verse was revealed when a Makkan disbeliever (reported to be Ubayy ibn Khalaf or al-'As ibn Wa'il) came to the Prophet with a decayed bone, crumbled it in his hands, and mockingly asked: 'Do you claim your Lord will bring this back to life?' This question, meant as a refutation of resurrection, actually reveals the questioner's ignorance. They could not imagine how scattered, decayed bones could be reassembled into living beings. But this is only difficult from a human perspective, not from Allah's perspective."
  },
  79: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"They will be revived by the One Who produced them the first time": "The answer is simple and irrefutable: the same One who created these bones the first time will bring them back to life. Initial creation is actually more remarkable than re-creation—creating from nothing is greater than recreating from something. If Allah originated life the first time, He can certainly restore it.",
    "for He has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of every created being": "Allah knows every creation perfectly—every bone, every particle, every cell. Nothing is lost or forgotten in His knowledge. Even when bones decay and scatter, when bodies return to dust, when atoms disperse across the earth—Allah knows exactly where every particle is and how to reassemble it. His knowledge encompasses every creation that has ever existed."
  },
  80: {
    "˹He is the One˺ Who gives you fire from green trees": "Allah presents another sign of His power to bring opposites together. Green trees are full of water and moisture—the opposite of fire. Yet from this green, wet wood, Allah enables fire to be kindled. Specifically, this refers to the Markh and 'Afar trees in Arabia, which when rubbed together produce fire even while green. If Allah can bring fire from water-filled wood—combining opposites—can He not bring life from dead bones?",
    "and —behold!—you kindle ˹fire˺ from them": "You yourselves witness this and use it regularly. You strike these green branches and fire emerges. This is not magic—it is Allah's design of nature. The One who designed such systems can certainly design resurrection. Every time they lit a fire from green wood, they witnessed a sign of Allah's power, yet they still denied resurrection."
  },
  81: {
    "Can the One Who created the heavens and the earth not ˹easily˺ resurrect these ˹deniers˺?\"": "The ultimate rhetorical question: the One who created the entire universe—the vast heavens with all their galaxies, stars, and planets, and the complex earth with all its systems—can He not recreate tiny human beings? The creation of the cosmos is infinitely greater than the creation of humans. If Allah accomplished the greater task, the lesser task is certainly within His power.",
    "Yes ˹He can˺!": "The answer is emphatic: 'Bala!'—Yes, absolutely! There is no doubt whatsoever. The question is rhetorical because the answer is obvious to anyone who reflects.",
    "For He is the Master Creator, All-Knowing": "Allah is 'Al-Khallaaq'—the Master Creator, the One who creates abundantly and repeatedly. He is also 'Al-'Aleem'—the All-Knowing, possessing complete knowledge of everything. With unlimited creative power and unlimited knowledge, nothing is beyond Allah's ability. Resurrection is not a challenge for Him; it is simply a matter of His will."
  },
  82: {
    "All it takes, when He wills something ˹to be˺, is simply to say to it: \"Be!\" And it is!": "This is the most powerful statement of Allah's absolute power: 'Kun fayakoon'—Be, and it is. When Allah wills something, He does not need materials, tools, time, or effort. He simply commands it to exist, and it exists. This applies to all creation—the heavens, the earth, humans, animals, resurrection, anything and everything. The entire universe came into existence through this command. Resurrection is no different—one command, and all the dead will rise. This verse demolishes any argument against Allah's power. Nothing is difficult for the One whose command is 'Be, and it is.'"
  },
  83: {
    "So glory be to the One in Whose Hands is the authority over all things": "The Surah concludes with glorification of Allah—'Subhan Allah.' He is far above any imperfection, any partner, any limitation. In His hands is 'malakoot'—the dominion, authority, and control of everything that exists. Nothing is outside His sovereignty. Every atom, every creature, every event is under His command. This is the Lord who has been described throughout the Surah—the Creator of the universe, the Sender of messengers, the One who gives life and death.",
    "and to Whom ˹alone˺ you will ˹all˺ be returned": "The final word is the ultimate reminder: everyone will return to Allah. There is no escape, no alternative destination, no avoiding this meeting. Whether one believes or disbelieves, whether one is prepared or not—the return to Allah is certain. This return is the culmination of everything: the purpose of creation, the reason for revelation, the meaning of life. Every person should ask themselves: am I prepared to meet my Lord? This ending ties back to the beginning of the Surah, which affirmed the Prophet's mission to warn humanity of this very return. May Allah make us among those who return to Him with sound hearts and receive His greeting of 'Salam' in Paradise."
  }
};